        output='Based on the provided document chunks, here is a detailed breakdown of the company\'s disclosures regarding xAI/Grok revenue, subscription and API revenue, enterprise customers, the Grok monetization model, and segment reporting:\n\n### 1. Segment Reporting and AI Revenue Breakdown\nThe company (SpaceX) operates three reportable segments: **Space**, **Connectivity**, and **AI**. The AI segment encompasses xAI, Grok, and X, operating as a highly vertically integrated AI platform. \n\nThe AI segment generates revenue from two primary streams:\n1.  **Advertising:** The sale of ad products displayed on the X platform.\n2.  **AI Solutions and Infrastructure:** This includes subscription-related offerings, data licensing arrangements, and API access to Grok models.\n\n**Recent Financial Performance (AI Segment):**\n*   **Full Year 2025:** Total company revenue increased by $581 million (22.2%) compared to 2024. This was driven by a $116 million increase in advertising revenue (from advertising partners on X) and a $465 million increase in AI solutions and infrastructure revenue. The AI solutions increase was mainly due to a $365 million jump in X and Grok subscription revenue and an $88 million increase in data licensing arrangements.\n*   **Q1 2026 (Three months ended March 31, 2026):** AI segment revenue increased by $91 million (12.5%) compared to Q1 2025. This was due to a $191 million increase in AI solutions and infrastructure revenue (driven by a $177 million increase in Grok and X subscription revenue and $12 million in data licensing), which offset a $100 million decrease in advertising revenue (caused by a short-term overhaul of the advertising platform).\n\n### 2. Grok Monetization Model and Subscription Revenue\nThe company monetizes Grok through a multi-tiered consumer subscription model, enterprise licensing, and API access. \n\n**Consumer Subscriptions:**\nThe company offers three tiers of subscription for Grok—basic, SuperGrok, SuperGrok Heavy, and SuperGrok Lite—priced on a monthly or annual basis. Higher pricing tiers unlock expanded access to advanced models, increased usage limits, priority compute, and premium features. \n*   **Subscriber Metrics:** As of March 31, 2026, the company reached approximately 6.3 million active paid subscribers across its ecosystem. This consisted of 4.4 million X Premium/Premium+ subscribers and 1.9 million SuperGrok, SuperGrok Heavy, and SuperGrok Lite paid subscribers.\n*   **Revenue Recognition:** Premium subscriptions on X and Grok are recognized ratably over the period of the subscription term, which ranges from month-to-month up to one year.\n*   **Future Monetization:** The company believes it is still early in increasing paid penetration across its Grok user base and sees an incremental monetization opportunity by introducing advertising into its stand-alone Grok offering.\n\n### 3. Enterprise Customers and API Revenue\nThe company is actively growing enterprise and government adoption of its AI offerings through tailored deployments. \n*   **Enterprise Products:** The company has launched **Grok Business**, **Grok Enterprise**, **Grok API**, and **xAI Gov**. These are sold on license-, consumption-, or outcome-based pricing models, customized to specific enterprise workflows and security needs.\n*   **API Revenue Recognition:** Revenue from providing API access to Grok models is recognized ratably over the contract term (typically month-to-month or up to one year) for stand-ready access, or as services are consumed for usage-based arrangements.\n*   **Strategic Partnerships:** The company is partnering with Cursor to advance Grok and create jointly-owned coding and knowledge work AI models. Additionally, Tesla\'s January 2026 investment in xAI (converted into SpaceX equity upon acquisition) has spawned collaborative AI initiatives like "Macrohard" (an agentic AI platform) and "Terafab" (an AI chip manufacturing initiative).\n\n### 4. Data Licensing Revenue\nAs part of its AI solutions and infrastructure stream, the company generates revenue from data licensing arrangements. \n*   **Revenue Recognition:** Data licensing revenue is generally recognized ratably over the period (from month-to-month up to two years) in which the company provides data as the customer consumes and benefits from the use of the licensed data. \n\n### 5. Advertising Monetization Strategy\nAdvertising remains a core monetization channel for the AI segment, primarily driven by the X platform. \n*   **Revenue Recognition:** Advertising revenue is recognized in the period the ad is delivered, evidenced by a user engaging with the ad in a manner satisfying the advertiser\'s selected criteria. For ads sold directly on X, the company acts as the principal and recognizes revenue gross. \n*   **AI-Driven Ad Strategy:** Grok increasingly supports advertising by helping advertisers with campaign creation, creative optimization, and alignment with trending topics. The company focuses on making ads feel like content—contextually relevant and integrated into real-time conversations.',
