    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='Based on the provided MD&A and financial statement excerpts, here is a detailed breakdown of what is disclosed regarding the AI segment’s costs, profitability, and standalone economics.\n\n### 1. Standalone Economics for Grok or xAI\nThe text does not isolate fully standalone financial statements for Grok or xAI. Instead, their financials are bundled into the broader "AI segment," which encompasses the Grok LLM, AI solutions, X (formerly Twitter), and data licensing. However, the text does attribute specific revenue and cost drivers directly to Grok and xAI:\n*   **Grok Revenue Drivers:** Revenue is generated through X and Grok subscriptions, data licensing arrangements, and API access to Grok models (recognized ratably over month-to-month to one-year terms, or as consumed for usage-based arrangements). \n*   **Grok/xAI Cost Drivers:** R&D expenses are heavily tied to the training of Grok, including the depreciation of GPU hardware, cloud computing costs, and data center infrastructure. The segment\'s massive capital expenditures (reaching $7.7 billion in Q1 2026) are primarily to scale compute infrastructure for Grok. \n\n### 2. Cost of Revenue and Gross Margin\nThe AI segment’s cost of revenue includes infrastructure costs (data center facilities, lease/hosting, energy, bandwidth, depreciation of servers/networking equipment, public cloud hosting), revenue share expenses, payment processor fees, payments to creators, amortization of acquired intangibles, and allocated labor/overhead.\n\n**Q1 2026 vs. Q1 2025:**\n*   **Cost of Revenue:** Increased by $5 million (1.1%), from $451 million to **$456 million**. This was driven by a $71 million increase in revenue share and content creator expenses and $18 million in higher payment processing fees, partially offset by other decreases.\n*   **Implied Gross Profit / Margin:** Revenue grew from $727 million to $818 million. This implies a gross profit of $362 million and a gross margin of **~44.3%** for Q1 2026, up from an implied gross margin of ~38.0% ($276 million gross profit) in Q1 2025.\n\n**Full Year 2025 vs. 2024:**\n*   **Cost of Revenue:** Increased by $491 million (29.1%), from $1,687 million to **$2,178 million**. Drivers included $412 million in higher infrastructure/cloud computing costs, $90 million in employee compensation, $45 million in revenue share/creator fees, and $28 million in payment processor fees.\n*   **Implied Gross Profit / Margin:** Revenue grew from $2,620 million to $3,201 million. This implies a gross profit of $1,023 million and a gross margin of **~31.9%** for 2025, down from an implied gross margin of ~35.6% ($933 million gross profit) in 2024.\n\n**Outlook:** The company expects AI cost of revenue to increase in absolute dollars as revenue grows, but *decrease as a percentage of revenue* (expanding gross margins) as it monetizes products and expands AI service offerings.\n\n### 3. Research and Development (R&D)\nR&D expenses relate primarily to training Grok, developing next-generation AI-enabled products, and data center costs. These costs include cloud computing, employee compensation, power generation, and depreciation of data center assets (processors, networking equipment).\n\n*   **Q1 2026:** R&D surged by $1,471 million to **$2,379 million** (up from $908 million in Q1 2025), driven by GPU hardware depreciation and cloud computing/data center infrastructure expenses.\n*   **Full Year 2025:** R&D increased by $3,888 million to **$5,064 million** (up from $1,176 million in 2024), driven by the same GPU depreciation and cloud computing factors.\n*   **Outlook:** The company expects R&D to continue increasing both in absolute dollars and as a percentage of revenue as it invests in compute infrastructure for Grok (and potentially due to a compute agreement with Cursor).\n\n### 4. Selling, General, and Administrative (SG&A)\nSG&A consists primarily of employee compensation for sales, marketing, finance, legal, IT, and HR, as well as professional services (consulting, content moderation, legal/accounting) and facilities overhead.\n\n*   **Q1 2026:** SG&A was **$463 million** (up from $300 million in Q1 2025).\n*   **Full Year 2025:** SG&A was **$1,827 million** (up from $1,105 million in 2024).\n*   **Outlook:** SG&A is expected to increase in absolute dollars to support growth but decrease as a percentage of revenue as the company reduces operating costs. It may also increase due to the Cursor compute agreement.\n\n### 5. Restructuring and Impairments\n*   **Restructuring:** AI segment restructuring charges are entirely attributed to the October 2022 acquisition of Twitter by X Holdings. Restructuring charges were $487 million in 2025, $213 million in 2024, $237 million in 2023, and $(11) million (a credit) in Q1 2026.\n*   **Impairments:** The segment recorded a massive $3,775 million impairment in 2023, but $0 in 2024 and 2025.\n\n### 6. Segment-Level Profitability, Operating Loss, and EBITDA\nThe AI segment is operating at a significant loss due to the heavy infrastructure investments outlined above.\n\n**Operating Loss (Income from operations):**\n*   **Q1 2026:** **$(2,469) million** (increased loss of $1,533 million from Q1 2025\'s $(936) million loss).\n*   **FY 2025:** **$(6,355) million** (increased loss of $4,794 million from 2024\'s $(1,561) million loss).\n*   **FY 2024:** **$(1,561) million** (improved from 2023\'s $(3,973) million loss).\n*   **FY 2023:** **$(3,973) million**.\n\n**Segment Adjusted EBITDA:** *(Defined as segment income/loss from operations excluding D&A, share-based compensation, restructuring, and impairment)*\n*   **Q1 2026:** **$(609) million** (decreased by $497 million from Q1 2025\'s $(112) million).\n*   **FY 2025:** **$(1,237) million** (decreased by $1,584 million from 2024\'s $347 million).\n*   **FY 2024:** **$347 million** (decreased by $875 million from 2023\'s $1,222 million).\n*   **FY 2023:** **$1,222 million**.\n\n**Outlook on Profitability:** The company explicitly states there is a "multi-year investment horizon" before deployments translate into sustained positive Segment Adjusted EBITDA for the AI segment.\n\n### 7. Capital Expenditures & Infrastructure KPI\nTo contextualize the costs and losses, the text reveals the massive scale of capital deployment and infrastructure growth:\n*   **Capital Expenditures:** \n    *   Q1 2026: **$7,723 million** \n    *   FY 2025: **$12,727 million**\n    *   FY 2024: **$5,633 million**\n    *   FY 2023: **$463 million**\n*   **Nameplate Compute Draw (KPI):** Grew from 0 gigawatts in 2023 to 0.3 GW in 2024, 0.8 GW in 2025, and 1.0 GW in Q1 2026.',
