s, $600 billion in digital advertising, and $22.7 trillion in enterprise applications.\n\nThe company notes this TAM excludes nascent, unquantified future markets that could eventually represent multi-trillion-dollar opportunities, such as long-haul point-to-point terrestrial travel, space tourism, in-orbit manufacturing, asteroid mining, and lunar/Mars energy production and transportation.\n\n### Enterprise AI Market Size\nThe company sizes the enterprise AI market by aligning it with the broader "digital economy." \n*   According to the Digital Cooperation Organization (DCO), the digital economy is estimated to reach approximately **$22.7 trillion in 2026**. \n*   The DCO estimates the digital economy will grow three times faster year-over-year in 2026 compared to global GDP growth. \n*   In a DCO survey, 69% of respondents identified AI and advanced analytics as their top digital technology priority, higher than any other surveyed priority.\n\n### Maturity of Enterprise Adoption\nThe company characterizes the enterprise AI space as being in its early stages, but experiencing rapid transformation:\n*   **Early Days:** The company explicitly states, "We believe we are still in the early days of AI transforming enterprises, with AI-powered enterprise applications poised to reshape the digital economy."\n*   **Current Adoption:** Despite being early, adoption is significant. As of February 2026, more than 80% of Fortune 500 companies were using AI active agents.\n*   **Impact on Workflows:** AI is currently being used to automate complex workflows, augment knowledge workers, and enhance decision-making. The company believes this transformation will ultimately evolve knowledge workers into "managers of autonomous agents," unlocking unprecedented creativity and productivity. Entire industries are already being reshaped by agentic commerce, "vibe coding," and autonomous driving.\n\n### Forward-Looking Statements on Enterprise Monetization\nThe company outlines several f